      <hedline>
        <hl1>Cuba's Other Celebrity: The Woodpecker</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Mary C Pearl letter on efforts to protect Cuba's endangered ivorybill woodpecker (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Elusive Ivorybill'' (Topics of The Times, May 24):</p>
        <p>You describe the magnificent, endangered woodpecker and its possible survival in the Sierra Maestra in Cuba.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Elusive Ivorybill'' (Topics of The Times, May 24):</p>
        <p>You describe the magnificent, endangered woodpecker and its possible survival in the Sierra Maestra in Cuba.</p>
        <p>Although the Audubon Society is giving technical support to concerned Cuban ornithologists, the fact is that the Cuban team was well prepared to locate and identify its endangered wildlife.</p>
        <p>We at Wildlife Preservation Trust International, of which I am executive director, have spent more than seven years working closely with our Cuban colleagues as they act to protect the island's rare birds and other species.</p>
        <p>Given the celebrity status of the ivorybill woodpecker among birders, it is understandable that the Audubon Society would want to draw attention to its possible location in Cuba. But increased tourism could negatively affect the woodpecker's habitat.</p>
        <p>MARY C. PEARL  Philadelphia, May 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
